#let images = (
  "18-1": (
    caption: [The digestion of food molecules through *hydrolysis reactions* (水解反应). These reactions ultimately release the subunit molecules of each food category, breaking down complex carbohydrates, proteins, and lipids into their simpler components.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-2": (
    caption: [The organs of the *digestive system* (消化系统). Shows the complete gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, including accessory organs like the liver, gallbladder, and pancreas.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-3": (
    caption: [The layers of the *gastrointestinal tract* (胃肠道). Illustrates the four distinct layers: mucosa, submucosa, muscularis externa, and serosa, each with specific functions in digestion and motility.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-4": (
    caption: [*Peristalsis* (蠕动) in the esophagus. Peristaltic waves are sequential contractions that propel food bolus from the pharynx to the stomach through coordinated smooth muscle activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-5": (
    caption: [Primary regions and structures of the stomach. Shows the anatomical divisions including the cardia, fundus, body, and pylorus, along with the gastric rugae that allow for stomach expansion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-6": (
    caption: [*Gastric pits* (胃小凹) and *gastric glands* (胃腺) of the stomach mucosa. Shows the different cell types including parietal cells (secreting HCl and intrinsic factor), chief cells (secreting pepsinogen), and mucous cells (secreting protective mucus).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-7": (
    caption: [Secretion of gastric acid by *parietal cells* (壁细胞). The apical membrane secretes H⁺ in exchange for K⁺ using a proton pump, while the basolateral membrane exchanges Cl⁻ for HCO₃⁻, demonstrating the mechanism of HCl secretion into the gastric lumen.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-8": (
    caption: [The activation of *pepsin* (胃蛋白酶). The gastric enzyme pepsinogen (inactive zymogen) is converted to active pepsin by HCl and by autocatalytic action of pepsin itself, initiating protein digestion in the stomach.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-9": (
    caption: [The *small intestine* (小肠). (a) The regions of the small intestine: duodenum, jejunum, and ileum, each specialized for different aspects of digestion and absorption.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-10": (
    caption: [The structure of an *intestinal villus* (肠绒毛). The figure depicts a villus with its epithelial cells, lacteal (lymphatic vessel), and blood capillaries, along with an intestinal crypt (crypt of Lieberkühn) where new epithelial cells are produced by mitosis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-11": (
    caption: [Electron micrograph of *microvilli* (微绒毛). Microvilli are evident at the apical surface of columnar epithelial cells, increasing surface area for absorption and containing brush border digestive enzymes embedded in their plasma membranes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-12": (
    caption: [Location of *brush border enzymes* (刷状缘酶). The brush border enzymes are embedded in the plasma membrane of microvilli, with their active sites facing the chyme in the lumen to complete digestion of food molecules.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-13": (
    caption: [*Segmentation* (分节运动) of the small intestine. Simultaneous contractions of numerous segments help mix the chyme with digestive enzymes and mucus, facilitating digestion and absorption.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-14": (
    caption: [*Slow waves* (慢波) in the intestine. Produced by interstitial cells of Cajal (ICC), these electrical waves pace smooth muscle contractions. The slow waves occur much slower than cardiac pacemaker potentials, with rates measured in seconds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-15": (
    caption: [Cells responsible for the electrical events within the *muscularis* (肌层). Interstitial cells of Cajal (ICC) generate slow waves that pace intestinal contractions, while autonomic neurons release neurotransmitters that modify electrical activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-16": (
    caption: [The *large intestine* (大肠). Illustrates the different regions of the colon including the cecum, ascending colon, transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, and rectum.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-17": (
    caption: [A photomicrograph of the human *appendix* (阑尾). This cross section reveals numerous lymphatic nodules that function in immunity, demonstrating the appendix's role in the immune system.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-18": (
    caption: [A radiograph of the large intestine. The large intestine is visualized after a barium enema, clearly showing the *haustra* (结肠袋), which are the sacculations characteristic of the colon.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-19": (
    caption: [Microscopic structure of the *liver* (肝脏). Blood enters a liver lobule through vessels in a portal triad, passes through hepatic sinusoids, and leaves via a central vein, which converges to form hepatic veins that transport venous blood from the liver.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-20": (
    caption: [The flow of blood and bile in a *liver lobule* (肝小叶). Blood flows within sinusoids from the portal vein to the central vein (periphery to center), while bile flows within hepatic plates from center to bile ductules at the periphery.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-21": (
    caption: [The *enterohepatic circulation* (肠肝循环). Substances secreted in bile may be absorbed by the intestinal epithelium and recycled to the liver via the hepatic portal vein, conserving bile salts and other compounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-22": (
    caption: [Simplified pathway for the metabolism of heme and *bilirubin* (胆红素). Heme from hemoglobin is converted to biliverdin, with iron recycled to bone marrow. Carbon monoxide (CO) is produced and must be eliminated due to its toxicity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-23": (
    caption: [The enterohepatic circulation of *urobilinogen* (尿胆原). Bacteria in the intestine convert bilirubin into urobilinogen. Some exits in feces, some is recycled through the liver, and some enters general circulation to be filtered by kidneys into urine.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-24": (
    caption: [*Bile acids* (胆汁酸) form *micelles* (微团). (a) Structure of cholic acid. (b) Simplified representation showing polar and nonpolar regions. (c) Bile acids aggregate in water to form micelles, which can incorporate cholesterol and lecithin, serving to emulsify triglycerides in the chyme.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-25": (
    caption: [The *pancreas* (胰腺) and pancreatic duct system. Shows how pancreatic secretions are delivered into the duodenum, with the pancreatic duct joining the common bile duct at the sphincter of ampulla (sphincter of Oddi).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-26": (
    caption: [*Gallstones* (胆结石) or biliary calculi. (a) Radiograph showing gallstones in gallbladder. (b) Posterior view of a surgically removed gallbladder (cholecystectomy) cut open to reveal gallstones.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-27": (
    caption: [The pancreas is both an *exocrine* (外分泌) and *endocrine* (内分泌) gland. (a) Relationship between endocrine and exocrine portions. (b) Exocrine pancreatic acini where acinar cells produce inactive enzymes stored in zymogen granules, secreted via duct system into duodenum.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-28": (
    caption: [Secretion of *bicarbonate* (碳酸氢盐) into pancreatic juice. Pancreatic duct cells use CO₂ from blood to generate carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which dissociates into HCO₃⁻ and H⁺. The HCO₃⁻ is secreted via a Cl⁻ exchanger, while Cl⁻ leaks back through CFTR chloride channels.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-29": (
    caption: [The activation of pancreatic juice enzymes. *Trypsinogen* (胰蛋白酶原), an inactive zymogen, is activated by brush border enzyme *enterokinase* (肠激酶) to form active trypsin. Active trypsin then activates other zymogens in pancreatic juice through a cascade mechanism.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-30": (
    caption: [The regulation of *gastric acid secretion* (胃酸分泌). Amino acids from digested proteins stimulate gastrin secretion from G cells, which is also stimulated by vagus nerve activity. Gastrin stimulates histamine release from ECL cells, which then acts as a paracrine regulator to stimulate parietal cells to secrete HCl.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-31": (
    caption: [The *enteric nervous system* (肠神经系统) coordinates peristalsis. Demonstrates local reflexes involving motor neurons, interneurons, and sensory neurons. Shows neurotransmitters that stimulate smooth muscle contraction and those causing relaxation (NO = nitric oxide; VIP = vasoactive intestinal peptide).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-32": (
    caption: [The action of *pancreatic amylase* (胰淀粉酶). Pancreatic amylase digests starch into maltose, maltriose, and short oligosaccharides containing branch points in the glucose chain.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-33": (
    caption: [The digestion and absorption of *proteins* (蛋白质). Polypeptide chains are digested into free amino acids, dipeptides, and tripeptides by pancreatic juice and brush border enzymes. These products enter epithelial cells, where dipeptides and tripeptides are hydrolyzed into free amino acids before secretion into capillaries and hepatic portal vein.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-34": (
    caption: [The digestion of *triglycerides* (甘油三酯). *Pancreatic lipase* (胰脂肪酶) digests fat by cleaving off the first and third fatty acids, producing free fatty acids and monoglycerides. Sawtooth lines indicate hydrocarbon chains in fatty acids.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-35": (
    caption: [Fat digestion and *emulsification* (乳化). Three steps show the fate of fat in the small intestine: digestion of triglycerides releases fatty acids and monoglycerides, which become associated with micelles of bile salts secreted by the liver.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18-36": (
    caption: [The absorption of fat. Fatty acids and monoglycerides from micelles are absorbed by epithelial cells and converted into triglycerides. These combine with protein to form *chylomicrons* (乳糜微粒), which enter lymphatic vessels (lacteals) of villi and transport to thoracic duct, emptying into venous blood.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-18-1": (
    caption: [*Brush Border Enzymes* (刷状缘酶) attached to the cell membrane of microvilli in the small intestine. Lists enzymes involved in final stages of carbohydrate and protein digestion, including disaccharidases and peptidases.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-18-2": (
